title: Aboriginal iron ore mine set for Pilbara
text:
View Photo 

Australia's first Aboriginal owned and operated iron ore mine is set to open in Western Australia's Pilbara, but only when the commodity's price is high enough. 
Fortescue Metals chief executive Nev Power has signed an agreement with Australian Aboriginal Mining Corporation for two million tonnes of iron ore each year for five years. 
AAMC says it will get access to Fortescue's infrastructure and can start mining "as soon as the prevailing commercial environment is supportive of such developments and funding activities have been sufficiently advanced". 
The price of iron ore has crashed almost 70 per cent since early 2013 before rallying in the past two months to about $US58 per tonne. @y7finance on Twitter, become a fan on Facebook Aboriginal iron ore mine set for Pilbara AAP
